SIMPLE: stew
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stew
<hw>Stew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Stow</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small pond or pool where fish
are kept for the table; a vivarium.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer. Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An artificial bed of oysters.</def> <mark>[Local,
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stew
<hw>Stew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stewed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stewing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>stuven</ets>, OF.
<ets>estuver</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tuver</ets>, fr. OF.
<ets>estuve</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tuve</ets>, a sweating house, a room
heated for a bath; probably of Teutonic origin, and akin to E.
<ets>stove</ets>. See <er>Stove</er>, and cf. <er>Stive</er> to
stew.]</ety> <def>To boil slowly, or with the simmering or moderate
heat; to seethe; to cook in a little liquid, over a gentle fire, without
boiling; <as>as, to <ex>stew</ex> meat; to <ex>stew</ex> oysters; to
<ex>stew</ex> apples</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1413 --></p>

<p><ent>Stew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stew
<hw>Stew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be seethed or
cooked in a slow, gentle manner, or in heat and moisture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stew
<hw>Stew</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>stue</ets>,
<ets>stuwe</ets>, OF. <ets>estuve</ets>. See <er>Stew</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place of stewing or seething; a place
where hot bathes are furnished; a hothouse.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As burning Aetna from his boiling <qex>stew</qex>⟦br⟧
Doth belch out flames.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lydians were inhibited by Cyrus to use any armor, and give
themselves to baths and <qex>stews</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Abp.
Abbot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A brothel; -- usually in the plural.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon. South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There be that hate harlots, and never were at the
<qex>stews</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Aschman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A prostitute.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir
A. Weldon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A dish prepared by stewing; <as>as, a
<ex>stew</ex>of pigeons</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A state of agitating excitement; a state of worry;
confusion; <as>as, to be in a <ex>stew</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steward</ent>⟦br⟧
